  "doc_id": "54279",
  "text": "Rheological profiles of the MCC grades were determined using a mixer torque rheometer (Caleva Process Solutions, Dorset, UK). Water, ethyl alcohol, IPA, and liquid mixtures were used as moistening liquids. Dry powder sample (15 g) was then introduced into the mixer bowl and mixed for 30 s. Torque generated by the dry powder was recorded for another 20 s. Moistening liquid, corresponding to an increment of 15% (v/w), was added to the powder in the mixer bowl with continuous mixing. After each mixing phase, the torque value was recorded for another 20 s prior to the next liquid addition, and mean torque values were calculated. The mean torque describes the mean resistance of the mass to mixing, i.e., the cohesive strength of moistened mass. The mean torque values generated for a total of 19 liquid additions were plotted against the amount of moistening liquid added. The plotted curve represents different states of liquid saturation. The peak region in the curve corresponds to the capillary state of liquid saturation [CITATION_1] .",
